  "prompt": "What is the use of a meta tag in HTML?",
  "response": "Meta tags in HTML are crucial for providing metadata about an HTML document. This metadata isn't displayed on the page itself but is used by browsers, search engines, and other web services to understand and process the document.  Think of them as little notes attached to your webpage providing extra information.\n\nHere's a breakdown of their uses:\n\n**1. Search Engine Optimization (SEO):**\n\n*   **`description`:**  Provides a brief summary of the page's content. Search engines often display this description in search results, influencing whether a user clicks on your link.  A well-written, compelling description is crucial for attracting visitors.\n*   **`keywords` (Less Important Nowadays):**  While less influential than they used to be, `keywords` can contain a list of relevant keywords related to the page's content. Search engines used to heavily rely on this tag for ranking, but its influence has diminished due to keyword stuffing abuses.  Google largely ignores this tag now, focusing more on on-page content.  However, some other search engines might still use it.\n*   **Robots Control (using `robots` attribute):**  This is a powerful meta tag that tells search engine crawlers how to treat the page.  You can tell them:\n    *   `index, follow`:  Index the page and follow all links on the page. (This is the default)\n    *   `noindex, follow`:  Do not index the page, but follow all links on the page.  Useful for pages with sensitive content or pages you don't want ranked.\n    *   `index, nofollow`:  Index the page, but do not follow links on the page.  Used to prevent passing link equity to linked pages.\n    *   `noindex, nofollow`:  Do not index the page and do not follow links on the page.  The strictest control; prevents the page from appearing in search results and prevents search engine spiders from following links on it.\n    *   `noarchive`:  Prevent search engines from caching the page.  This means a \"cached\" version of the page won't be available in search results.\n    *   `nosnippet`:  Prevent search engines from displaying a snippet (description) of the page in search results.\n    *   `unavailable_after:[date]`:  Indicates that the page should be removed from search results after a specific date.\n\n**2. Browser Behavior:**\n\n*   **`charset`:**  Specifies the character encoding for the document (e.g., `UTF-8`). This ensures that text is displayed correctly, especially with international characters.  `UTF-8` is almost universally recommended.  Example: `<meta charset=\"UTF-8\">`\n*   **`viewport`:** Controls how the webpage is displayed on different devices (especially mobile devices).  It's crucial for responsive web design.  A common example:  `<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">`\n    *   `width=device-width`: Sets the width of the viewport to match the device's screen width.\n    *   `initial-scale=1.0`: Sets the initial zoom level when the page is first loaded.\n*   **HTTP-equiv attributes (e.g., `refresh`):**  While generally discouraged in modern web development in favor of server-side redirects and JavaScript, these meta tags can instruct the browser to perform certain actions:\n    *   **`refresh`:**  Can be used to automatically redirect the user to another page after a specified time interval or to refresh the current page.  Example: `<meta http-equiv=\"refresh\" content=\"5;url=https://www.example.com\">` (redirects after 5 seconds). Avoid using this unless absolutely necessary as it's disruptive to the user experience.\n    *   **`content-type`:**  While the `charset` meta tag is preferred for specifying character encoding, this was formerly used for that purpose too.  Less common now.\n*   **X-UA-Compatible:**  Forces certain versions of Internet Explorer to render the page in a specific compatibility mode. This is mostly relevant for older websites that need to work correctly in older versions of IE.  Example: `<meta http-equiv=\"X-UA-Compatible\" content=\"IE=edge\">` (tells IE to use the latest rendering engine).\n\n**3. Social Media:**\n\n*   Meta tags are essential for controlling how your content is displayed when shared on social media platforms.  These are often called \"Open Graph\" (for Facebook and others) and \"Twitter Card\" tags.\n    *   **`og:title`:** The title of your content when shared on Facebook.\n    *   **`og:description`:** A description of your content when shared on Facebook.\n    *   **`og:image`:** The URL of an image to be displayed when the content is shared.\n    *   **`og:url`:** The canonical URL of the page.\n    *   **`twitter:card`:**  Specifies the type of Twitter Card to use (e.g., \"summary,\" \"summary_large_image\").\n    *   **`twitter:title`:** Title for Twitter card.\n    *   **`twitter:description`:** Description for Twitter card.\n    *   **`twitter:image`:**  Image for Twitter card.\n\n**4. Other Uses:**\n\n*   **Author:**  Specifies the author of the document (`<meta name=\"author\" content=\"John Doe\">`).\n*   **Copyright:**  Indicates the copyright information for the document (`<meta name=\"copyright\" content=\"Copyright 2023 Your Company\">`).\n*   **Generator:**  Identifies the software used to create the document (e.g., `<meta name=\"generator\" content=\"WordPress 6.3\">`).\n*   **Application Name:** Used for web applications to define the application name.  `<meta name=\"application-name\" content=\"MyWebApp\">`\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nMeta tags are vital for:\n\n*   **Search engine optimization:** Helping search engines understand your content.\n*   **Browser compatibility:** Ensuring correct display across different browsers and devices.\n*   **Social media sharing:**  Controlling how your content appears when shared.\n*   **Providing general metadata:**  Information about the document's author, copyright, etc.\n\n**Where to Put Meta Tags:**\n\nMeta tags always go within the `<head>` section of your HTML document.\n\n**Example:**\n\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n  <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n  <title>My Awesome Website</title>\n  <meta name=\"description\" content=\"This is a description of my website. It will show up in search results.\">\n  <meta name=\"keywords\" content=\"website, awesome, example\">\n  <meta name=\"author\" content=\"Your Name\">\n  <meta name=\"robots\" content=\"index, follow\">\n\n  <!-- Social Media Meta Tags (Open Graph) -->\n  <meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"My Awesome Website\">\n  <meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"This is a description of my website when shared on Facebook.\">\n  <meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"https://www.example.com/images/logo.png\">\n  <meta property=\"og:url\" content=\"https://www.example.com\">\n\n  <!-- Social Media Meta Tags (Twitter Card) -->\n  <meta name=\"twitter:card\" content=\"summary_large_image\">\n  <meta name=\"twitter:title\" content=\"My Awesome Website\">\n  <meta name=\"twitter:description\" content=\"This is a description of my website when shared on Twitter.\">\n  <meta name=\"twitter:image\" content=\"https://www.example.com/images/logo.png\">\n\n</head>\n<body>\n  <h1>Welcome to My Awesome Website!</h1>\n  </body>\n</html>\n```\n\nIt's important to choose and configure your meta tags carefully to achieve the desired effect and improve your website's visibility and usability.  While `keywords` is less important, the other meta tags, especially `description`, `viewport`, and social media meta tags, are critical for a well-optimized website.\n",
